On a rectangular grid as shown below, how many of the given four triangles are isosceles?

{{DGM:8f6305f15c462316}}
$\text{(A)}\ 1 \qquad \text{(B)}\ 2 \qquad \text{(C)}\ 3 \qquad \text{(D)}\ 4 \qquad \text{(E)}\ 0$

Ahmed rolls five standard six-sided dice and observes that the product of the numbers shown on the upper faces is $720$. Which of the following could not be the sum of the upper faces?
{The options will be added after solving the problem}
$\mathrm{(A) \ }20 \qquad \mathrm{(B) \ }21 \qquad \mathrm{(C) \ }22 \qquad \mathrm{(D) \ }23 \qquad \mathrm{(E) \ }24$

Pegs are put in a board $1$ unit apart both horizontally and vertically. A rubber band is stretched over $5$ pegs, forming a shape as shown in the figure. The points are (0,1), (1,2), (3,2), (4,1), and (2,0) on the coordinate grid. Calculate the area of this shape in square units.
{{DGM:5069a1f65b58a86f}}
$\mathrm{(A)}\ 6 \qquad \mathrm{(B)\ } 6.5 \qquad \mathrm{(C)\ } 7 \qquad \mathrm{(D)\ } 7.5 \qquad \mathrm{(E)\ } 8$
